Introduction¶

Different stimuli evoke different brain response, which allows an organism to respond to a stimulus of a particular kind in a particular way. Therefore an interesting question that can be asked about the brain-stimuli relationship is: can one predict the stimuli by looking at the evoked brain response?

In this paroject, dynamic brain activity patterns of human subjects, captured by fMRI, in response to approaching and retreating threats is used to predict the stimulus class.

What is fMRI data?¶

  • Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI) is a timeseries data.

  • Like a movie of the brain.

  • Each frame (timepoint) is a 3D volume.

  • The unit of the 3D volume is a voxel (analogous to pixel of a 2D image).

  • Dimensions of a voxel is generally 3mm x 3mm x 3mm.

  • Rate at which fMRI data is collected is commonly referred to as repetition time (TR).

  • Commonly used TR is 0.5-2 seconds per volume. TR = 1.25 seconds for the current study.

Typical fMRI setup¶

  • Participant views a visual stimuli on a projection screen via a mirror mounted to the scanner’s head coil.

  • Head coil measures the brain signal.

A) Participant in the fMRI scanner, B) Head coil with a mounted mirror, C) Full setup schematic.

Methods¶

Procedure & Visual Stimuli¶

  • fMRI data was collected on 61 participants.

  • Forty-five minutes of fMRI data was collected on every participant.

  • Two circles moved around randomly on the projection screen.

  • When circles collided, an unpleasant mild electric shock was delivered to the index and middle fingers of participant’s left hand.

  • Shock delivery was only meant to induce fear of circle collision.

  • Several events of “near-miss” occured at random times during the experiment.

  • Near-miss events are defined as those when the circles approach each other for at least 8 seconds, come very close (i.e., distance less than 1.5 times the circle diameter), but miss and start to retreat, again, at least for 8 seconds.

  • Near-miss events were included to investigate brain’s dynamic response to approaching and retreating threats.

Preprocessing¶

  • fMRI timeseries data suffers from a lot of noise such as,

    • Physiological signals associated with respiratory and cardiac cycles.

    • Head motion.

    • Scanner noise (drifts).

  • These noise were filtered out using ICA (https://fsl.fmrib.ox.ac.uk/fsl/fslwiki/).

Training Data¶

  • Out of the 45 minute long timeseries data, “segments” corresponding to near-miss events were extracted.

  • Each segment was 14 timepoints long (14 x 1.25 = 17.5 seconds): first 7 timepoints corresponded to approach, and later 7 to retreat.

  • Every participant had 46 segments. That is, approximately 13 out 45 minutes of data was used for model training.

  • Following is an example of a segment from the parietal cortex of the brain.

  • Training segments from a total of 316 brain regions were extracted in a similar fashion.

  • Following figure shows all the brain regions.

  • Every segment was divided into two training examples and labeled accordingly as follows:

                           <----------- Timeseries --------------->       Label  
  training example 1: [TP00, TP01, TP02, TP03, TP04, TP05, TP06] -> "approach"  
  training example 2: [TP07, TP08, TP09, TP10, TP11, TP12, TP13] -> "retreat"

  • Problem with this kind of training segments is that the trained model will not make an accurate prediction unless the cricles have already been aproaching (or retreating) for at least 8 seconds.

  • To make the model more robust to change in the direction of the circles (from approach to retreat and vise-versa), five more timepoints from past were included for every training example, while keeping the effective length of the training example consistent (i.e., 7 timepoints.). For example, the training exmaple 1 shown above was extended as follows:

                              <-------------------------------  Time  ------------------------------------->
     training example 1:                                  [TP00, TP01, TP02, TP03, TP04, TP05, TP06] -> "approach"  
                                                   [-TP01, TP00, TP01, TP02, TP03, TP04, TP05]       -> "approach"
                                            [-TP02, -TP01, TP00, TP01, TP02, TP03, TP04]             -> "approach"
                                     [-TP03, -TP02, -TP01, TP00, TP01, TP02, TP03]                   -> "approach"
                              [-TP04, -TP03, -TP02, -TP01, TP00, TP01, TP02]                         -> "approach"
                       [-TP05, -TP04, -TP03, -TP02, -TP01, TP00, TP01]                               -> "approach"

  • Retreat segments were extended in the same fashion. Following shows the original segments and their extensions.

  • Out of 61 participants, only 42 participants data was used to train and validate the predictive model. Remaining 19 participants data was used to test the model.

Model¶

A Reccurent Neural Network (RNN) with Gated Recurrent Units (GRU) was used to build a predictive model. The RNN had three hidden layers, each with 16 GRU units, and a dense output layer with single unit. binary_crossentropy was used as the loss function which was minimized using an Adam optimizer. Following was the model architecture:

Results¶

Accuracy across cross-validation (cv) folds¶

Optimal hyper-parameters for L2 regularization, dropout and learning rate were found using a grid-search, 5-fold CV appraoch. Best performing model yielded an accuracy of 0.86 and 0.77 on training and validation sets. Hyperparameters of the best performing model were: L2 regularization of 0.001, dropout rate of 0.4, and learning rate of 0.001. Following plot shows mean accruary across CV folds.
